From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: sarun <noreply@sarun>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 17:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Refresh exports after recipe eval

GNU make permits `$(eval ...)` during recipe expansion. If it changes an
exported variable, recipes sequenced after that expansion and recursive makes
must inherit the new value. The in-process runner materializes exports as an
evaluator-owned shell prefix rather than mutating the process environment, so
refresh that prefix immediately after the eval statements run.

Linux arm64 uses this relation to append its per-task stack-canary flags in the
`stack_protector_prepare` recipe before recursive Kbuild makes compile objects.
Leaving the parse-time prefix unchanged compiled modules against the global
`__stack_chk_guard` and failed at modpost.

---
diff --git a/src-rs/func.rs b/src-rs/func.rs
index 4ec6501..278361d 100644
--- a/src-rs/func.rs
+++ b/src-rs/func.rs
@@ -556,7 +556,11 @@ fn eval_func(args: &[Arc<Value>], ev: &mut Evaluator, _out: &mut dyn BufMut) ->
         );
     }
     let stmts = parse_buf(&text, ev.loc.clone().unwrap_or_default())?;
-    ev.eval_stmts(&stmts)
+    ev.eval_stmts(&stmts)?;
+    // A recipe-time eval can change an exported variable. Recipes and
+    // in-process recursive makes use the evaluator-owned environment prefix,
+    // so materialize the new state at the same sequence point as GNU make.
+    ev.refresh_box_export_prefix()
 }
 
 // A hack for Android build. We need to evaluate things like $((3+4))
-- 
2.43.0
